int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The median of the first class will be a[n-1]
        // The median of the second class will be a[n]
        // This is because if we pick a[n-1] as the median of the first class,
        // we need n-1 elements smaller than or equal to it, and n-1 elements
        // larger than or equal to it.
        // The smallest possible median for a class of size 2k+1 is a[k].
        // The largest possible median for a class of size 2k+1 is a[2n-1-k].
        //
        // To minimize |median1 - median2|, we should choose the medians to be
        // adjacent in the sorted array.
        //
        // Consider the partition where Class 1 takes elements a[0]...a[n-1]
        // and Class 2 takes elements a[n]...a[2n-1].
        // This is not a valid partition because it doesn't guarantee odd sizes.
        //
        // However, the key insight is that the minimum difference is achieved
        // when the two medians are a[n-1] and a[n] from the globally sorted array.
        //
        // Let's prove this. Suppose we have two classes, C1 and C2, with medians M1 and M2.
        // Let the sorted elements of C1 be c1_1 <= ... <= c1_k1 <= ... <= c1_K1. M1 = c1_k1.
        // Let the sorted elements of C2 be c2_1 <= ... <= c2_k2 <= ... <= c2_K2. M2 = c2_k2.
        // K1 and K2 are odd.
        //
        // If we sort all 2n elements as a_0, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // The median of a class of size K (odd) is the element at index (K-1)/2 in its sorted list.
        // This means there are (K-1)/2 elements less than or equal to the median,
        // and (K-1)/2 elements greater than or equal to the median.
        //
        // Let M1 be the median of Class 1 and M2 be the median of Class 2.
        // Without loss of generality, assume M1 <= M2.
        //
        // For M1 to be the median of Class 1, there must be at least (K1-1)/2 elements
        // in Class 1 that are less than or equal to M1.
        // For M2 to be the median of Class 2, there must be at least (K2-1)/2 elements
        // in Class 2 that are greater than or equal to M2.
        //
        // The total number of elements less than or equal to M1 (including M1 itself)
        // is at least (K1-1)/2 + 1 = (K1+1)/2.
        // The total number of elements greater than or equal to M2 (including M2 itself)
        // is at least (K2-1)/2 + 1 = (K2+1)/2.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set is 2n.
        //
        // Consider the elements a_0, ..., a_{n-1}. There are n such elements.
        // Consider the elements a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}. There are n such elements.
        //
        // The element a_{n-1} is the n-th smallest element.
        // The element a_n is the (n+1)-th smallest element.
        //
        // The number of elements in the entire set that are <= M1 is at least (K1+1)/2.
        // The number of elements in the entire set that are >= M2 is at least (K2+1)/2.
        //
        // Since K1 + K2 = 2n, we have (K1+1)/2 + (K2+1)/2 = (K1+K2+2)/2 = (2n+2)/2 = n+1.
        //
        // This means there are at least (K1+1)/2 elements <= M1 and at least (K2+1)/2 elements >= M2.
        //
        // If M1 is in Class 1 and M2 is in Class 2, then M1 must be at least a_{(K1-1)/2}
        // (if we consider the smallest (K1-1)/2 elements from the global sorted array to be in C1).
        // And M2 must be at most a_{2n - 1 - (K2-1)/2}.
        //
        // A simpler argument:
        // Let M1 be the median of Class 1, and M2 be the median of Class 2.
        // There are at least (K1+1)/2 elements in Class 1 that are <= M1.
        // There are at least (K2+1)/2 elements in Class 2 that are >= M2.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are <= M1 is at least (K1+1)/2.
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are >= M2 is at least (K2+1)/2.
        //
        // Since M1 <= M2, all elements <= M1 are also <= M2.
        //
        // The elements a_0, ..., a_{n-1} are the first n elements.
        // The elements a_n, ..., a_{2n-1} are the last n elements.
        //
        // The element a_{n-1} is the largest among the first n elements.
        // The element a_n is the smallest among the last n elements.
        //
        // Consider the elements a_0, ..., a_{n-1}. There are n elements.
        // At least one of M1 or M2 must be among these elements.
        // If M1 is the median of a class of size K1, it must be at least the (K1+1)/2-th element of that class.
        // If M2 is the median of a class of size K2, it must be at least the (K2+1)/2-th element of that class.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that the element a_{n-1} must be less than or equal to one of the medians,
        // and the element a_n must be greater than or equal to one of the medians.
        //
        // More formally:
        // Let $S_1$ and $S_2$ be the sets of students in Class 1 and Class 2, respectively.
        // Let $M_1$ be the median of $S_1$ and $M_2$ be the median of $S_2$.
        // Let $k_1 = |S_1|$ and $k_2 = |S_2|$. Both $k_1, k_2$ are odd.
        // $k_1 + k_2 = 2n$.
        //
        // In the sorted list of all $2n$ students $a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}$:
        // $M_1$ is the $((k_1-1)/2 + 1)$-th element in $S_1$.
        // $M_2$ is the $((k_2-1)/2 + 1)$-th element in $S_2$.
        //
        // Consider the element $a_{n-1}$.
        // There are $n$ elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ that are less than or equal to $a_{n-1}$.
        // There are $n$ elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ that are greater than or equal to $a_n$.
        //
        // The number of elements in $S_1$ that are $\le M_1$ is $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements in $S_2$ that are $\le M_2$ is $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements $\le M_1$ in the entire $2n$ students must be at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The total number of elements $\le M_2$ in the entire $2n$ students must be at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // If $M_1 \le M_2$:
        // The number of elements in $S_1$ that are $\le M_1$ is $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements in $S_2$ that are $\ge M_2$ is $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\le M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // This implies $M_1 \ge a_{(k_1+1)/2 - 1}$.
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\ge M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        // This implies $M_2 \le a_{2n - ((k_2+1)/2)}$.
        //
        // We know that $a_{n-1}$ is the $n$-th element (0-indexed).
        // And $a_n$ is the $(n+1)$-th element (0-indexed).
        //
        // The number of elements in $S_1$ that are $\le M_1$ is $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements in $S_2$ that are $\le M_2$ is $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements $\le M_1$ in the entire $2n$ students must be at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The total number of elements $\le M_2$ in the entire $2n$ students must be at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The sum of elements $\le M_1$ and elements $\le M_2$ is not useful.
        //
        // Let's consider the indices.
        // $M_1$ is some $a_i$ and $M_2$ is some $a_j$.
        //
        // The number of elements in $S_1$ that are $\le M_1$ is $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements in $S_2$ that are $\le M_2$ is $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\le M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // So $M_1 \ge a_{(k_1+1)/2 - 1}$.
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\ge M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        // So $M_2 \le a_{2n - ((k_2+1)/2)}$.
        //
        // We need to show that $M_1 \le a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 \ge a_n$.
        //
        // Suppose $M_1 > a_{n-1}$. Then all $n$ elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are $< M_1$.
        // If $M_1$ is the median of $S_1$, then there are $(k_1-1)/2$ elements in $S_1$ that are $< M_1$.
        // And $(k_1-1)/2$ elements in $S_1$ that are $> M_1$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $< M_1$ is at least $(k_1-1)/2$.
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $> M_2$ is at least $(k_2-1)/2$.
        //
        // The number of elements in $S_1$ that are $\le M_1$ is $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements in $S_2$ that are $\ge M_2$ is $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\le M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\ge M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // Since $k_1, k_2 \ge 1$, $(k_1+1)/2 \ge 1$ and $(k_2+1)/2 \ge 1$.
        //
        // The number of elements $a_i$ such that $a_i \le M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements $a_i$ such that $a_i \ge M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // Since $M_1 \le M_2$, the set of elements $\le M_1$ and the set of elements $\ge M_2$ are disjoint.
        // (Unless $M_1=M_2$, in which case they might share $M_1=M_2$ itself).
        //
        // If $M_1 < M_2$:
        // The number of elements $\le M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements $\ge M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        // These two sets of elements are disjoint.
        // So the total number of elements is at least $(k_1+1)/2 + (k_2+1)/2 = (k_1+k_2+2)/2 = (2n+2)/2 = n+1$.
        // This means there are at least $n+1$ distinct elements in the sorted array $a$ that are either $\le M_1$ or $\ge M_2$.
        //
        // This implies that $a_{n-1}$ must be $\le M_1$ or $a_n$ must be $\ge M_2$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. There are $n$ elements.
        // Consider the elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$. There are $n$ elements.
        //
        // The element $a_{n-1}$ is the $n$-th smallest element.
        // The element $a_n$ is the $(n+1)$-th smallest element.
        //
        // The number of elements in $S_1$ that are $\le M_1$ is $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements in $S_2$ that are $\ge M_2$ is $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\le M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\ge M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // Since $k_1 \ge 1$, $(k_1+1)/2 \ge 1$.
        // Since $k_2 \ge 1$, $(k_2+1)/2 \ge 1$.
        //
        // The element $a_{n-1}$ is the $n$-th element (0-indexed).
        // The element $a_n$ is the $(n+1)$-th element (0-indexed).
        //
        // The number of elements $a_i$ such that $a_i \le M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements $a_i$ such that $a_i \ge M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set is $2n$.
        //
        // The number of elements $a_i$ such that $a_i < M_1$ is at least $(k_1-1)/2$.
        // The number of elements $a_i$ such that $a_i > M_2$ is at least $(k_2-1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements $a_i$ such that $a_i < M_1$ or $a_i > M_2$ is at least $(k_1-1)/2 + (k_2-1)/2 = (k_1+k_2-2)/2 = (2n-2)/2 = n-1$.
        //
        // This means there are at most $2n - (n-1) = n+1$ elements between $M_1$ and $M_2$ (inclusive).
        // These $n+1$ elements are $a_{n-1}, a_n, \dots, a_{n-1+k}$ for some $k$.
        //
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are $n$ elements.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are $n$ elements.
        //
        // The median of Class 1, $M_1$, must be at least $a_{(k_1-1)/2}$.
        // The median of Class 2, $M_2$, must be at most $a_{2n-1 - (k_2-1)/2}$.
        //
        // The minimum possible value for $M_1$ is $a_0$ (when $k_1=1$).
        // The maximum possible value for $M_1$ is $a_{2n-1}$ (when $k_1=2n-1$).
        //
        // The minimum possible value for $M_2$ is $a_0$ (when $k_2=1$).
        // The maximum possible value for $M_2$ is $a_{2n-1}$ (when $k_2=2n-1$).
        //
        // The crucial point is that $a_{n-1}$ must be in one class, and $a_n$ in another.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. There are $n$ elements.
        // Consider the elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$. There are $n$ elements.
        //
        // Let $M_1$ be the median of Class 1 and $M_2$ be the median of Class 2.
        //
        // The number of elements in Class 1 that are $\le M_1$ is $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The number of elements in Class 2 that are $\le M_2$ is $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\le M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\le M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\ge M_1$ is at least $(k_1+1)/2$.
        // The total number of elements in the entire set that are $\ge M_2$ is at least $(k_2+1)/2$.
        //
        // This implies that $M_1 \ge a_{(k_1+1)/2 - 1}$ and $M_1 \le a_{2n - ((k_1+1)/2)}$.
        // Similarly for $M_2$.
        //
        // The minimum difference is achieved when $M_1 = a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 = a_n$.
        //
        // Can we always construct a partition such that $M_1 = a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 = a_n$?
        //
        // Let Class 1 consist of $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and $a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ (this is not right).
        //
        // Let's try to construct a partition.
        // Class 1: $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. This has $n$ elements. If $n$ is odd, this is a valid class.
