        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks to minimize |median(C1) - median(C2)|.
        // After sorting the entire array, the optimal strategy is to
        // assign the smallest n elements to one class and the largest n elements
        // to the other class.
        // Specifically, the median of the first class will be a[n-1]
        // and the median of the second class will be a[n].
        // This is because if we take any other elements, say a[i] and a[j]
        // where i < n-1 or j > n, then we could potentially move elements
        // to make the medians closer.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // We need to pick two medians, say m1 and m2.
        // To minimize |m1 - m2|, we want m1 and m2 to be as close as possible.
        //
        // If we partition the students into two classes, C1 and C2,
        // such that |C1| = 2k1+1 and |C2| = 2k2+1, and (2k1+1) + (2k2+1) = 2n.
        // This implies 2(k1+k2+1) = 2n, so k1+k2+1 = n.
        // The median of C1 is its (k1+1)-th element.
        // The median of C2 is its (k2+1)-th element.
        //
        // The key insight is that the minimum difference is achieved when the
        // two medians are adjacent elements in the sorted full array.
        // Specifically, a[n-1] and a[n].
        //
        // We can form a class C1 of size 2k1+1 and C2 of size 2k2+1.
        // To make a[n-1] the median of C1, we need to pick k1 elements smaller than a[n-1]
        // and k1 elements larger than a[n-1] (from the remaining elements).
        // To make a[n] the median of C2, we need to pick k2 elements smaller than a[n]
        // and k2 elements larger than a[n] (from the remaining elements).
        //
        // The simplest partition that achieves this is:
        // Class 1: {a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1}}
        // Class 2: {a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}}
        // This partition is not valid because both classes have size n, which might be even.
        //
        // However, the problem states that each class must have an odd number of students.
        // The smallest possible odd size for a class is 1.
        // The largest possible odd size for a class is 2n-1.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // We want to pick two medians $m_1, m_2$.
        // To minimize $|m_1 - m_2|$, we should pick $m_1$ and $m_2$ to be as close as possible.
        // The closest possible values for medians, given the structure of the problem,
        // are $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
